                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d993">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/390: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-19T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 19, 1937—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 19—6:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>827. My 817, October 16, 1 [<hi rend="italic">3</hi>] p.m.<note n="95"
                        xml:id="d993fn95">Not printed.</note> The British Chargé d’Affaires informed
                    me yesterday that the Minister for Foreign Affairs told him confidentially
                    October 16 that he himself regarded preservation of the Customs Administration
                    as the paramount issue and that he would be willing to accept the original
                    Japanese proposal for the Tientsin area if that were the best arrangement
                    possible. He said that <pb facs="0884" n="877" xml:id="pg_877"/> he would
                    attempt to obtain the concurrence of his colleagues but he anticipated great
                    difficulty.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department, repeated to Peiping and Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
